R & RStudio

  • R is an open-source programming environment.
  • R is used for data analysis, graphics and statistical computing.
  • R language is widely used among statisticians for developing statistical software and data analysis.

RStudio

  • RStudio is Rs popular front-end or integrated development environment (IDE) for R and Python.
  • We will use RStudio for all class related computation and analysis.
  • RStudio provides syntax highlighting, code completion and smart indentation.
  • Some of RStudios features includes
    • plot history, zooming, and flexible image and PDF export;
    • integrated R help and documentation;
    • generating word or pdf file output;
    • searchable command history.

R and RStudio Interface

RStudio Cloud

  • We can implement R programs without installing R (and RStudio) locally!
  • RStudio Cloud lets you do, share and learn statistics and data science online for free!

Install RStudio Cloud

  • Step 1: In the RStudio website https://rstudio.com/, choose Products > posit cloud as shown below.
  • Step 2: Click GET STARTED FOR FREE.
  • Step 3: Choose the free plan, and click Sign Up. Use your Marquette email address, or signup with GitHub if you use it often.
  • Step 4: Once you login, you should be able to see RStudio Cloud as shown below!

New Projects

  • In RStudio Cloud, click New Project, then you are all set!

First R Code in RStudio Cloud

  • Give your project a nice name (click Untitled Project), math-4931 for example.

Install R and RStudio Locally to Your Computer

Install R Step 1

  • Click Download R for [your operating system]

Install R and RStudio Locally to Your Computer

Working in RStudio/RStudio Cloud

RStudio Panes

Working in RStudio/RStudio Cloud

R Script

  • A R script is a .R file that contains R code.
  • To create a R script, go to File > New > R Script, or click the green-plus icon on the top left corner, and select R Script.

Working in RStudio/RStudio Cloud

Run Code

  • Run: run the current line or selection of code.
    • ctrl + enter (Windows) or cmd + enter (Mac)
  • Icon right to the Run: re-run the previous selected code.
    • shift + ctrl + p (Windows) or shift + cmd + enter (Mac)
  • Source: run all the code in the R script.

Environment Tab

  • The (global) environment is our workspace (NOT the RStudio Cloud workspace).
  • Anything created or imported into the current R session is stored in our environment and shown in the Environment tab.
  • After we run the R script, objects stored in the environment are
    • Data set mtcars
    • Object x storing integer values 1 to 10.
    • Object y storing three numeric values 3, 56, 2.

History Tab

  • The History tab keeps a record of all previous commands.
  • save icon: save all history to a file
  • To Console: send the selected commands to the R console.
  • To Source: inserted the selected commands into the current R script.

R Packages

  • R packages are a collection of reusable R functions, code and data.
  • When we start a R session, only built-in packages like base, stats, etc are available.
  • Installing a package is an easy way to access to others data and functions. ### Installing R Packages
  • To install a package, for example, the ggplot2 package, we use the command
install.packages("ggplot2")

R Packages

Loading R Packages

  • Once the package is installed, we can load the package into our R session using library() function to use any function or data in ggplot2:
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(mpg, aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=class)) + geom_point()

  • Without loading the package, to use any function or data in ggplot2, we have to add ggplot2:: before calling the function or data.
ggplot2::ggplot(mpg, aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=class)) + ggplot2::geom_point()

Help

  • Dont know how a function works or what a data set is about ?
  • Simply type ? followed by the data name or function name like
## starting httpd help server ... done
  • A document will show up in the Help tab, teaching you how to use the function or explaining the data set.
